					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Making a tracker work with the NES controller doesn't sound more exiting to place .db statements in notepad to me. If the tracker is made to play files with a cool viewer and not to edit them then it's another story.</div>
<br />
<br />Mr Cup-Is-Half-Empty.... <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />
<br />
<br />I've always wrote NES music in a text file so I know what you mean. However, a native tracker offers some advantages such as live tweaking of sounds which could be useful both in a compositional use and a "live" use - give you the ability to "mix" a song in real time. Kind of like LSDJ....but on NES.
<br />
<br />(Though I don't actually know much about LSDJ so I could be talking rubbish <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /> )</div>

